In fact this is due to composite (instead of RF). RF is the cause of more intereference on the screen due to sound signal career and other RF perturbation.<br /><br />If you ever used S-Video (or even better, RGB), those "dot crawls" are gone. Of course this is not possible with a NES since it directly outputs composite.<br /><br />On a side note I find the dot crawls especially noticeable on the PAL NES. They aren't nearly as noticeable on a NTSC NES or a PAL SNES.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=38">Bregalad</a> — Thu May 26, 2011 11:24 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
